jwst.title: Webb First Deep Field
jwst.subtitle: Galaxy cluster SMACS 0723, and it is teeming with thousands of galaxies including the faintest objects ever observed in the infrared

jwst.title: The Pillars of Creation
jwst.subtitle: A small region within the vast Eagle Nebula, which lies 6,500 light-years away. Newly formed stars are the scene-stealers in this image

jwst.title: Pandoras's Cluster
jwst.subtitle: Never-before-seen details in a region of space known as Pandoras Cluster (Abell 2744)

jwst.title: Cosmic Cliffs
jwst.subtitle: Galaxy cluster SMACS 0723. Rare peek into stars in their earliest, rapid stages of formation. For an individual star, this period only lasts about 50,000 to 100,000 years.

jwst.title: Seyfert galaxy
jwst.subtitle: 19 galaxies targeted for study by the Physics at High Angular resolution in Nearby Galaxies (PHANGS) collaboration. Nearby barred spiral galaxy NGC 1433

jwst.title: Earendel
jwst.subtitle: The most distant single star ever found

jwst.title: Stephan's Quintet
jwst.subtitle: A visual grouping of five galaxies, is best known for being prominently featured in the holiday classic film, “Its a Wonderful Life.

jwst.title: Southern Ring Nebula
jwst.subtitle: The bright star at the center of NGC 3132. A second star, barely visible at lower left along one of the bright stars diffraction spikes, is the nebulas source.

jwst.title: A Cosmic Tarantula
jwst.subtitle: Image stretching 340 light-years across, displays the star-forming region in a new light,

jwst.title: Cosmic Seahorse
jwst.subtitle: A galaxy cluster in the foreground has magnified distant galaxies. gravitational lensing, occurs when a massive celestial object such as a galaxy cluster causes a sufficient curvature of spacetime for light to be visibly bent around it

jwst.title: Cartwheel Galaxy
jwst.subtitle: Located about 500 million light-years away in the Sculptor constellation, is a rare sight. Its appearance, much like that of the wheel of a wagon, is the result of an intense event

jwst.title: A Wolf Rayet Star
jwst.subtitle: Massive stars race through their lifecycles, and only some of them go through a brief Wolf-Rayet phase before going supernova

jwst.title: Orion Nebula
jwst.subtitle: Believed to be the cosmic fire of creation by the Maya of Mesoamerica, M42 blazes brightly in the constellation Orion

jwst.title: Galactic Get-Together
jwst.subtitle: II ZW 96 is roughly 500 million light-years from Earth and lies in the constellation Delphinus, close to the celestial equator. As well as the wild swirl of the merging galaxies, a menagerie of background galaxies are dotted throughout the image.

jwst.title: GOODS-S field
jwst.subtitle: Portion of an area of the sky known as GOODS-South, which has been well studied by the Hubble Space Telescope and other observatories. More than 45,000 galaxies are visible here.

jwst.title: Chameleon I
jwst.subtitle: An in-depth inventory of the deepest, coldest ices measured to date in a molecular cloud. In addition to simple ices like water, the team was able to identify frozen forms of a wide range of molecules

jwst.title: protostar
jwst.subtitle: The protostar itself is hidden from view within the “neck” of this hourglass shape. An edge-on protoplanetary disk is seen as a dark line across the middle of the neck.
